  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><p align="center">Shari's Mission Statement</p>
      <p align="center">To enhance the value of our guests' overall dining experience by <u><strong>identifying and developing</strong></u> extremely talented and caring employees dedicated to serving quality products with pride.<br>
        <br>
    </p>    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><div align="left">
      <p>Shari's Mission Statement says it all - the way we are going to achieve our goal of enhancing the dining experience for our guest is by finding and then developing the right employees. Notice that our mission statement doesn't say that we enhance the guests' dining experience by controlling food cost, achieving budget or saving labor hours. While these things are important, they are not the main focus - they are a byproduct or end result of accomplishing the mission of satisfying guests who will return. As hard as managers work, they cannot do everything themselves. To achieve guest satisfaction, profit and sales growth they must choose good employees and work through them. Bottom line, identifying, hiring, training and developing is the reason we have managers. Basically, how well you perform in these four key areas determines your success as a manager. </p>
      <p>The management of people determines organizational success. Training cannot wait until &quot; the manager gets around to it' or &quot;when time permits.&quot; A manager must do many things at once. All are important, but nothing is <em>more</em> important than training. In this reading assignment we will be discussing the training philosophies and the manager's role in training at Shari's.<br>
        <br>
      </p>
    </div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/training_images/training_graphic.JPG" width="463" height="469" border="1"><br>
      <br>
    </div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2">Hopefully we can all agree that training is a necessity - but it can cost a lot! Not only do you have a trainee's wage, you also have to pay someone to train them. Let's take a moment then to consider how the store will benefit from their investment in training.<br> </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<table width="640" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><strong>Saving Money:</strong> If employees know how to do work the <em>right</em> way, costs will be lower; profits will be higher. Food cost , workman comp and labor are some examples of areas where we can save money by training our employees.<br>      <br> </td>
    <td width="153"><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/tied_money.JPG" width="85" height="67" border="1"></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="130"><img src="../../../images/waitess2.gif" width="164" height="177"></td>
    <td colspan="2"><strong>Make More Money: </strong>Would it be reasonable to expect that a well trained server will be able to achieve a higher PPE? If we can assume that is just 10 cents and a server waits on 90 guests per day, bring in an extra $9.00 in sales. Multiply that over the employment life of the server and it can be a lot. If you take advantage of all the server training opportunities you have (contest roll-outs, meeting topics, training videos and initial training, you can have a big impact on your store's sales. <br></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3"><p><strong>Saving Employees:</strong> Employees who are trained perform better. Employees who perform well are less anxious and more confident in their abilities. They don't get flustered or frustrated easily. This will reduce turnover.<em>The cost of turnover for an hourly employee is $1,300! </em></p>
    <p><strong>Saving Customers and Making New Ones:</strong> Customers are happy when they receive the products or services they expect. Training helps assure that this consistently happens. <br>
      <br>
    </p>    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2"><strong>Saves Time: </strong>A trained staff will perform more efficiently. They understand expectations and teamwork. The are better able to think on their own and act, rather than react, when situations occur. This can save time and labor costs.<br>      <br></td>
    <td><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/clock.gif" width="50" height="47"></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3"><strong>Saves Relationships:</strong> Managers who show their concern for employees with quality training help motivate them and morale levels are likely to increase. <br></td>
  </tr>
</table>
