<interaction name="MultCh_Radios01" object="G01" template="010_Multiple Choice/020_MultCh_Radios_03.agt" includesrc="interactionClass.js,elemInptClass.js">
<div name="G01Layer"> </div>
</interaction>
<blockquote>	
  <table width="640" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><div align="left">
        <p>We know that training can be costly - is there a way to know that our money and effort will pay off? Since training doesn't work in every situation, a good manager continually evaluates his or her employees to see where they are in the attitude/knowledge continuum, remembering that employees can move in and out of these four categories. Good managers provide the right style of leadership for attitude and the right amount of training for job knowledge.<br>
          <br>
        </p>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/training_images/training_graphic2.JPG" width="601" height="319"><br>
        <br>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width="560">Training styles or the delivery have a lot to do with the employee's acceptance and the effectiveness of training. Have you ever been in a training session and felt lost, frustrated, insulted or unmotivated - these feeling are all a result of using the wrong delivery method for the participant's level of competency and awareness. There are basically four levels of learning and matching training styles. Click <a href="learning_levels.htm">here</a> or on the icon to go exploring! <br></td>
      <td width="73"><a href="learning_levels.htm"><img src="../../../images/this_way.gif" alt="Go explore" width="70" height="93" border="0"></a><a name="return"></a></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"> <interaction name="Explore_Areas08" object="G08" template="030_Explore/030_Explore_Areas_04.agt" includesrc="interactionClass.js,elemHotaClass.js,behDragLayer.js">
      <div name="G08Layer"> </div>
      </interaction> </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><div align="center">
        <p>Shari's Four-Step Training Process</p>
        <p align="left">Another item that we use at Shari's to ensure that training is effective is an organized and consistent system for training. We call this the four-step training process. Shari's Training Guide for each job code is set up to assist with the four step process. Get a Server Trainer Guide to follow along as we discuss the tools used in each step. </p>
        <p align="left"><u>Step One - Preparation</u> </p>
        <div align="left">
          <ul>
            <li>Put the learner at ease - we use a friendly attitude and make the learner feel welcome</li>
            <li>Tell them about the job and find out what they already know - this way the trainer can adjust the training and it also gives the new employee an opportunity to talk about their abilities.</li>
            <li>Get the learner interested in the job - let them know why the job is done and how it will benefit them.</li>
            </ul>
          <p>Tools to help the trainer prepare - Daily Training Plan and Trainee Schedule </p>
          <p><u>Step Two - Presentation</u></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Tell, show, and illustrate each element of the job, one at a time.</li>
            <li>Instruct clearly, slowly and completely - trainees need time off the floor or line to accomplish this.</li>
            <li>Stress key points while demonstrating - attach importance</li>
            </ul>
          <p>Tools to help the trainer present - Job Code Manuals, Videos, Workbooks, Laminated Job Aids, Job Code Reference Binder (Tools are listed on training plans as they are used). </p>
          <p><u>Step Three - Performance by the Learner</u></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Learner does the job, trainer corrects errors</li>
            <li>Learner repeats back key points</li>
            <li>Learner repeats job until he understands</li>
            </ul>
          <p>Tools to help the trainer evaluate performance - Job Description, Skills Checklist, Job Code Tests </p>
          <p><u>Step Four - Follow-up and Critique</u></p>
          <ul>
            <li>Let the learner go by them self.</li>
            <li>Advise whom to ask in case of trouble.</li>
            <li>Trainer checks frequently as a coach.</li>
            <li>Commend a job well done</li>
            <li>Taper off coaching </li>
            </ul>
          <p>Tools to assist the training in follow-up and critique: Training File Index, Administration Checklist, Test Results, Shift Reports </p>
        </div>
        <div align="left"></div>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr bordercolor="#000033">
      <td colspan="2">Log into the <a href="http://university.sharis.com/chat" target="_blank">chat</a> room at 3:45 for a discussion on &quot;Training At Shari's&quot; - Bring a Server Trainer Guide and Server Trainer Manual with you.<br> </td>
    </tr>
